&gt;
&gt;  I actually thought of a good reason for using Ate-Roe instead of Et-Roe
&gt;  for the SQUARE set.
&gt;
&gt;  Consider the words &quot;ferry&quot; and &quot;fairy&quot;. All non-rhotics and some rhotics
&gt;  pronounce them differently, whereas many rhotics make them the same.
&gt;  What are the lexical sets?
&gt;
&gt;  Non-rhotics make &quot;ferry&quot; DRESS and &quot;fairy&quot; FACE, with the /r/ in the
&gt;  next syllable in both cases (which is why it&#39;s pronounced; non-rhotics
&gt;  don&#39;t drop /r/ at the beginning of a syllable.) For rhotics who do
&gt;  distinguish between the two, &quot;ferry&quot; is likewise DRESS with the /r/
&gt;  belonging to the second syllable, whereas &quot;fairy&quot; is definitely SQUARE.
&gt;  For rhotics who merge, both &quot;fairy&quot; and &quot;ferry&quot; are SQUARE.
&gt;
&gt;  So if we use Et-Roe for SQUARE, what are we to use for DRESS when /r/
&gt;  follows? If we use Ate-Roe, though, &quot;fairy&quot; is Fee-Eat-Roe-It, whereas
&gt;  &quot;ferry&quot; is Fee-Et-Roe-It.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;  &gt; And one warning. Some Australians may want to keep terminal
&gt;  &gt; unstressed &quot;Eat&quot; written as #27Eat, rather than #26It.
&gt;
&gt;  Just about the only reason to keep HAPPY (final unstressed /i/) as It
&gt;  rather than Eat is that Read prescribes it (it was standard RP in his
&gt;  day, though it no longer is). Otherwise only a few varieties use it;
&gt;  I&#39;d be happy to have everyone else use Eat.
